General Overview:
>All of Meganium’s evolutionary forms are mild mannered, friendly, gentle grass types that are extremely easy to care for,
>In the wild, the Bayleef and its evolutions do nothing but wander about the low temperate plains and forests, soaking up fresh water and bright sunlight in herds, or, more scientifically, “meadows”, of around 8-20 members.
>Differently to many other Pokemon that live in large groups, these meadows of Meganium don’t seem to have any leader or pecking order.
>In all of my years, I have not once seen a conflict escalate within one of these groups. This is perhaps because of the mind-affecting pollen and scents that these Pokemon produce that keep them, and even predators, too mellow and docile to become violent.
>When a meadow becomes too large, a “Pruning Event” will occur, where roughly half of the meadow parts ways with the other, with adolescent Bayleef often choosing to wander off on their own to form their own meadow.
>Those with stronger, sweeter-smelling aromas will always accumulate more members.
>These adolescents are what I would recommend trainers catching, but you can’t really go wrong with catching any of these Pokemon.
>You can find meadows sunbathing by clean, shallow, rocky streams during the spring, summer and early fall.
>At the first sign of a bite of cold in the air, Meganium meadows will begin a sudden migration to warmer areas.
>This might be the only danger this Pokemon might possess; thoughtlessly throwing yourself into their stampede during this event.
>Don’t bother battling them and weakening them before throwing a Pokeball like you would with most.
>Depending on their resistance to it, the pollen and aroma of these groups can completely prevent a trainer and their Pokemon from attacking at all.
>Notably, a few species of native bug-types are immune to the effects of the smell. Heracross is a constant worry for Meganium, as their sweet scent ironically only helps the bug-type locate them. A Heracross will not kill any of the members, thankfully.
>They love the sweet, medicinal sap that is held within Bayleef’s neck-appendages, intended to be energy stores, possibly for its eventual evolution. A feeding Heracross might delay a Bayleef’s evolution by weeks or months, but won’t actually harm the creature.
